    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1863-06-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1863-06-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="219" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d219">
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Adams</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Seward</persName>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 434.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,
                                        <hi rend="italic">London,</hi>
                        </placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1863-06-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 19, 1863.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> Your attention will doubtless have been
                            drawn to the report of a debate in the House of Lords, on Monday
                            evening, the 15th instant, on the questions raised by the Earl of
                            Clanricarde respecting the action of the United States vessels on the
                            ocean. It will be some cause of satisfaction to you to find both Lord
                            Russell and the Duke of Somerset ready to bear testimony to the fairness
                            of the proceedings of the commanders, and particularly to the deportment
                            of Admiral Wilkes. Considering the predisposition that unquestionably
                            prevails here to find fault with everything done on the part of the
                            United States, it is rather a causes of congratulation to find that the
                            steady policy of the government is gradually compelling testimony to its
                            comity, in the execution of its conceded rights.</p>
                <p>I have the honor to be, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>CHARLES FRANCIS ADAMS.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>Hon. <hi rend="smallcaps">William H. Seward,</hi>
                        <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State, Washington, D. C.</hi>
                    </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
